Now, we need to prove the equality. Let's expand the definitions.

`RelIO.liftFinf n f` is `fin_range n |>.map (λ i => ⟨↑i.toNat, f i⟩) |>.toAssocList`.
`fin_range n` is `List.replicate n 0`.
So, `fin_range n |>.map (λ i => ⟨↑i.toNat, f i⟩)` is `List.replicate n 0 |>.map (λ i => ⟨↑i.toNat, f i⟩)`.
This results in `List.replicate n ⟨0, f 0⟩`.
Then, `toAssocList` converts this list to an `AssocList`.

So, `RelIO.liftFinf n f` is an `AssocList Nat α` with keys `0, 1, ..., n-1` and values `f 0, f 1, ..., f (n-1)`.

`mapVal (λ x => g) (RelIO.liftFinf n f)` maps `g` over the values of the `AssocList`. The result is an `AssocList Nat β` with the same keys and values `g (f 0), g (f 1), ..., g (f (n-1))`.

The right-hand side `RelIO.liftFinf n (λ i => g (f i))` is `fin_range n |>.map (λ i => ⟨↑i.toNat, g (f i)⟩) |>.toAssocList`. This is an `AssocList Nat β` with keys `0, 1, ..., n-1` and values `g (f 0), g (f 1), ..., g (f (n-1))`.

So, we need to prove that `mapVal (λ x => g) (RelIO.liftFinf n f)` equals `RelIO.liftFinf n (λ i => g (f i))`.

Let's write the proof:

